               <physDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                    <p>Halantas. Final N (l8, l16) is a simplified na, reduced and raised, without a headmark. Final T is like a full-sized ta with a curly tail (l18); a character in l16 lacks this tail and so I read it as ta, emending to T, while LR reads it as T. Final M (l29) is a circle with a vertical tail, slightly smaller than regular characters.</p>
                    <p>Original punctuation marks are plain short verticals, floating around median height.</p>
                    <p>Other palaeographic observations. Dependent o is often written with a cursive single stroke. The two-stroke form is found e.g. in l7 ātmajo. l8 tanujo and trayodaśa. Dependent au (e.g. l2) differs from cursive o in being conspicuously extended to the footline, and its humps are also slightly asymmetrical. Rare initial Ai occurs in line 28.
